</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The duodenum, the first portion of the small bowel, is divided into four segments and extends to both retro- and intraperitoneal spaces. Some conditions arise primarily from the duodenum, but it can be secondarily affected by processes that involve neighboring structures. When duodenal emergencies are not identified and treated promptly, they may result in high morbidity and mortality. Imaging plays an important role in the diagnosis of duodenal conditions in the acute setting. However, the radiologic findings can be subtle, and awareness of relevant patient history and clinical presentation is important as it may increase the index of suspicion and one’s ability to diagnose these conditions. Duodenal peptic disease is common and can be complicated by bleeding and perforation. The duodenum can be secondarily involved by pancreatitis and gallbladder pathologic conditions and may be affected by iatrogenic complications following endoscopic procedures. Traumatic injuries to the duodenum are generally uncommon, with penetrating traumatic injury being the most frequent mechanism of injury. Duodenal vascular pathologic conditions such as aortoduodenal fistula are uncommon but can be life threatening. The knowledge of which pathologic condition can involve which duodenal segment can help the radiologist establish a differential diagnosis and achieve a more targeted imaging approach.</div><div role="paragraph"><a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/do/10.1148/rg.2020200045.pres/full/"><i>The online slide presentation from the RSNA Annual Meeting is available for this article.</i></a></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200045">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200045">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal anatomy. Drawing (a) and coronal CT image (b) show the anatomic relationships of the duodenum: stomach (black *), first segment of the duodenum (green arrow; green area in a), second segment of the duodenum (pink arrow; pink area in a), third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow; yellow area in a), fourth segment of the duodenum (orange arrow; orange area in a), gallbladder (brown * and brown area in a), pancreas (brown arrow), aorta (white * and red area in a), and inferior vena cava (IVC) (blue * and blue area in a)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig1a.jpeg" height="1285" width="1212" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Duodenal anatomy. Drawing <b>(a)</b> and coronal CT image <b>(b)</b> show the anatomic relationships of the duodenum: stomach (black *), first segment of the duodenum (green arrow; green area in <b>a</b>), second segment of the duodenum (pink arrow; pink area in <b>a</b>), third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow; yellow area in <b>a</b>), fourth segment of the duodenum (orange arrow; orange area in <b>a</b>), gallbladder (brown * and brown area in <b>a</b>), pancreas (brown arrow), aorta (white * and red area in <b>a</b>), and inferior vena cava (IVC) (blue * and blue area in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal anatomy. Drawing (a) and coronal CT image (b) show the anatomic relationships of the duodenum: stomach (black *), first segment of the duodenum (green arrow; green area in a), second segment of the duodenum (pink arrow; pink area in a), third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow; yellow area in a), fourth segment of the duodenum (orange arrow; orange area in a), gallbladder (brown * and brown area in a), pancreas (brown arrow), aorta (white * and red area in a), and inferior vena cava (IVC) (blue * and blue area in a)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig1b.jpeg" height="1289" width="1241" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Duodenal anatomy. Drawing <b>(a)</b> and coronal CT image <b>(b)</b> show the anatomic relationships of the duodenum: stomach (black *), first segment of the duodenum (green arrow; green area in <b>a</b>), second segment of the duodenum (pink arrow; pink area in <b>a</b>), third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow; yellow area in <b>a</b>), fourth segment of the duodenum (orange arrow; orange area in <b>a</b>), gallbladder (brown * and brown area in <b>a</b>), pancreas (brown arrow), aorta (white * and red area in <b>a</b>), and inferior vena cava (IVC) (blue * and blue area in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. (a) Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in a–d) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). (b) Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). (d) Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig2a.jpeg" height="1135" width="1178" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in <b>a–d</b>) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. (a) Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in a–d) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). (b) Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). (d) Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig2b.jpeg" height="1136" width="991" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in <b>a–d</b>) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. (a) Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in a–d) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). (b) Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). (d) Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig2c.jpeg" height="1136" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in <b>a–d</b>) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. (a) Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in a–d) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). (b) Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). (d) Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig2d.jpeg" height="1170" width="1198" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Anatomic relationships of the duodenum at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the first segment of the duodenum (dashed outline in <b>a–d</b>) and the gallbladder (white arrow) and IVC (green arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows the second segment of the duodenum and the liver (*), common bile duct (orange arrow), portal vein (red arrow), and pancreatic duct (purple arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows the third segment of the duodenum and the SMA (blue arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image shows the fourth segment of the duodenum and the duodenojejunal junction (green arrow) and aorta (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old man. (a) Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows outpouching in the duodenum, filled with contrast material (arrow). (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows outpouching (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Endoscopic image shows an ulcer with a small focal bleed (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig3a.jpeg" height="1212" width="1067" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows outpouching in the duodenum, filled with contrast material (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows outpouching (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows an ulcer with a small focal bleed (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old man. (a) Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows outpouching in the duodenum, filled with contrast material (arrow). (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows outpouching (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Endoscopic image shows an ulcer with a small focal bleed (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig3b.jpeg" height="1211" width="1191" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows outpouching in the duodenum, filled with contrast material (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows outpouching (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows an ulcer with a small focal bleed (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old man. (a) Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows outpouching in the duodenum, filled with contrast material (arrow). (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows outpouching (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Endoscopic image shows an ulcer with a small focal bleed (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig3c.jpeg" height="1212" width="1439" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image shows outpouching in the duodenum, filled with contrast material (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows outpouching (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows an ulcer with a small focal bleed (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. (a) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). (d) Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig4a.jpeg" height="967" width="1032" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. (a) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). (d) Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig4b.jpeg" height="967" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic" aria-label="Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. (a) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). (d) Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig4c.jpeg" height="966" width="1212" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic" aria-label="Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. (a) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). (d) Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig4d.jpeg" height="972" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Hemorrhagic duodenal ulcer in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the arterial phase shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) into the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen obtained in the portal venous phase shows an increase in extravasation (arrow), indicating active hemorrhage. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows active bleeding (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic image shows a bleeding ulcer (arrow), which was treated with clipping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="Perforated duodenal ulcer in an 81-year-old woman who underwent oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT of the upper abdomen. (a) Coronal CT image shows small foci of extraluminal gas (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image shows extraluminal extravasation of oral contrast material (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) in orange owing to iodine uptake by the oral contrast material."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig5a.jpeg" height="1121" width="1226" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Perforated duodenal ulcer in an 81-year-old woman who underwent oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT of the upper abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows small foci of extraluminal gas (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows extraluminal extravasation of oral contrast material (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) in orange owing to iodine uptake by the oral contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Perforated duodenal ulcer in an 81-year-old woman who underwent oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT of the upper abdomen. (a) Coronal CT image shows small foci of extraluminal gas (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image shows extraluminal extravasation of oral contrast material (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) in orange owing to iodine uptake by the oral contrast material."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig5b.jpeg" height="1125" width="1287" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Perforated duodenal ulcer in an 81-year-old woman who underwent oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT of the upper abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows small foci of extraluminal gas (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows extraluminal extravasation of oral contrast material (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) in orange owing to iodine uptake by the oral contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="Perforated duodenal ulcer in an 81-year-old woman who underwent oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT of the upper abdomen. (a) Coronal CT image shows small foci of extraluminal gas (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image shows extraluminal extravasation of oral contrast material (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) in orange owing to iodine uptake by the oral contrast material."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig5c.jpeg" height="1125" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Perforated duodenal ulcer in an 81-year-old woman who underwent oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT of the upper abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image shows small foci of extraluminal gas (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows extraluminal extravasation of oral contrast material (arrow) adjacent to the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine overlay dual-energy CT image shows contrast material extravasation (arrow) in orange owing to iodine uptake by the oral contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal ulcer complicated by abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. (a) Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a gas-containing fluid collection (dashed oval), contiguous within the second segment of the duodenum and displacing the pancreatic head (arrow) anteriorly. (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series obtained after pigtail catheter placement to drain the abscess shows the pigtail catheter (arrow) terminating in the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Axial CT image obtained following pigtail catheter placement shows a decrease in the size of the abscess (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig6a.jpeg" height="1255" width="1201" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Duodenal ulcer complicated by abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a gas-containing fluid collection (dashed oval), contiguous within the second segment of the duodenum and displacing the pancreatic head (arrow) anteriorly. <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series obtained after pigtail catheter placement to drain the abscess shows the pigtail catheter (arrow) terminating in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained following pigtail catheter placement shows a decrease in the size of the abscess (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal ulcer complicated by abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. (a) Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a gas-containing fluid collection (dashed oval), contiguous within the second segment of the duodenum and displacing the pancreatic head (arrow) anteriorly. (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series obtained after pigtail catheter placement to drain the abscess shows the pigtail catheter (arrow) terminating in the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Axial CT image obtained following pigtail catheter placement shows a decrease in the size of the abscess (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig6b.jpeg" height="1255" width="1168" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Duodenal ulcer complicated by abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a gas-containing fluid collection (dashed oval), contiguous within the second segment of the duodenum and displacing the pancreatic head (arrow) anteriorly. <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series obtained after pigtail catheter placement to drain the abscess shows the pigtail catheter (arrow) terminating in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained following pigtail catheter placement shows a decrease in the size of the abscess (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal ulcer complicated by abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. (a) Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a gas-containing fluid collection (dashed oval), contiguous within the second segment of the duodenum and displacing the pancreatic head (arrow) anteriorly. (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series obtained after pigtail catheter placement to drain the abscess shows the pigtail catheter (arrow) terminating in the second segment of the duodenum. (c) Axial CT image obtained following pigtail catheter placement shows a decrease in the size of the abscess (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig6c.jpeg" height="1255" width="1144" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Duodenal ulcer complicated by abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a gas-containing fluid collection (dashed oval), contiguous within the second segment of the duodenum and displacing the pancreatic head (arrow) anteriorly. <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series obtained after pigtail catheter placement to drain the abscess shows the pigtail catheter (arrow) terminating in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained following pigtail catheter placement shows a decrease in the size of the abscess (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Flowchart shows the CT features of peptic ulcer disease."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig7.jpeg" height="794" width="1899" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Flowchart shows the CT features of peptic ulcer disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Inflammatory conditions of the duodenum. (a) Duodenitis in a 64-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with periduodenal fat stranding, suggestive of duodenitis (arrow). (b, c) Groove pancreatitis in a 36-year-old woman with epigastric pain and elevated lipase levels. Axial (b) and coronal (c) contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky pancreatic head (*), with peripancreatic stranding and fluid (arrows in b). Note the thickening of the second segment of the duodenum, with periduodenal stranding and trace fluid (arrow in c)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig8a.jpeg" height="1254" width="1224" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Inflammatory conditions of the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Duodenitis in a 64-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with periduodenal fat stranding, suggestive of duodenitis (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Groove pancreatitis in a 36-year-old woman with epigastric pain and elevated lipase levels. Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky pancreatic head (*), with peripancreatic stranding and fluid (arrows in <b>b</b>). Note the thickening of the second segment of the duodenum, with periduodenal stranding and trace fluid (arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Inflammatory conditions of the duodenum. (a) Duodenitis in a 64-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with periduodenal fat stranding, suggestive of duodenitis (arrow). (b, c) Groove pancreatitis in a 36-year-old woman with epigastric pain and elevated lipase levels. Axial (b) and coronal (c) contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky pancreatic head (*), with peripancreatic stranding and fluid (arrows in b). Note the thickening of the second segment of the duodenum, with periduodenal stranding and trace fluid (arrow in c)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig8b.jpeg" height="1253" width="1163" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Inflammatory conditions of the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Duodenitis in a 64-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with periduodenal fat stranding, suggestive of duodenitis (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Groove pancreatitis in a 36-year-old woman with epigastric pain and elevated lipase levels. Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky pancreatic head (*), with peripancreatic stranding and fluid (arrows in <b>b</b>). Note the thickening of the second segment of the duodenum, with periduodenal stranding and trace fluid (arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="Inflammatory conditions of the duodenum. (a) Duodenitis in a 64-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with periduodenal fat stranding, suggestive of duodenitis (arrow). (b, c) Groove pancreatitis in a 36-year-old woman with epigastric pain and elevated lipase levels. Axial (b) and coronal (c) contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky pancreatic head (*), with peripancreatic stranding and fluid (arrows in b). Note the thickening of the second segment of the duodenum, with periduodenal stranding and trace fluid (arrow in c)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig8c.jpeg" height="1254" width="1312" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Inflammatory conditions of the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Duodenitis in a 64-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with periduodenal fat stranding, suggestive of duodenitis (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Groove pancreatitis in a 36-year-old woman with epigastric pain and elevated lipase levels. Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bulky pancreatic head (*), with peripancreatic stranding and fluid (arrows in <b>b</b>). Note the thickening of the second segment of the duodenum, with periduodenal stranding and trace fluid (arrow in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Bouveret syndrome in an 82-year-old woman. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a 3-cm gallstone (arrow) in the first segment of the duodenum, with a choledochoduodenal fistula (arrowhead). (b) Coronal CT image shows pneumobilia (arrow) and extensive periduodenal stranding (arrowhead). (Case courtesy of Daniel Souza, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig9a.jpeg" height="1226" width="1284" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Bouveret syndrome in an 82-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a 3-cm gallstone (arrow) in the first segment of the duodenum, with a 