third segments of the duodenum, with enhancing mucosa (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial MR enterographic image shows a distended stomach with significant luminal narrowing and stricture (arrow) of the second and third segments of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Postpolypectomy syndrome in a 42-year-old man who underwent biopsy of a duodenal polyp on the previous day. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows extensive fat stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second and third segments of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image shows stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second segment of the duodenum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig11a.jpeg" height="1257" width="1357" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Postpolypectomy syndrome in a 42-year-old man who underwent biopsy of a duodenal polyp on the previous day. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows extensive fat stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second and third segments of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second segment of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Postpolypectomy syndrome in a 42-year-old man who underwent biopsy of a duodenal polyp on the previous day. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows extensive fat stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second and third segments of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image shows stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second segment of the duodenum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig11b.jpeg" height="1257" width="1591" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Postpolypectomy syndrome in a 42-year-old man who underwent biopsy of a duodenal polyp on the previous day. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows extensive fat stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second and third segments of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows stranding and wall thickening (arrow) of the second segment of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal trauma. (a) Duodenal contusion in a 63-year-old man following a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT angiogram shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with hyperattenuation, likely a duodenal hematoma (white arrow) with adjacent hemoperitoneum (*). Note the devascularization of the left kidney owing to injury to the left renal artery (black arrow). (b, c) Duodenal hematoma in a 65-year-old man following blunt trauma to the abdomen. Axial (b) and coronal (c) CT angiograms of the abdomen show a high-attenuation collection centered in the second and third segments of the duodenum, consistent with hematoma (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig12a.jpeg" height="920" width="1355" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Duodenal trauma. <b>(a)</b> Duodenal contusion in a 63-year-old man following a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT angiogram shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with hyperattenuation, likely a duodenal hematoma (white arrow) with adjacent hemoperitoneum (*). Note the devascularization of the left kidney owing to injury to the left renal artery (black arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Duodenal hematoma in a 65-year-old man following blunt trauma to the abdomen. Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT angiograms of the abdomen show a high-attenuation collection centered in the second and third segments of the duodenum, consistent with hematoma (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal trauma. (a) Duodenal contusion in a 63-year-old man following a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT angiogram shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with hyperattenuation, likely a duodenal hematoma (white arrow) with adjacent hemoperitoneum (*). Note the devascularization of the left kidney owing to injury to the left renal artery (black arrow). (b, c) Duodenal hematoma in a 65-year-old man following blunt trauma to the abdomen. Axial (b) and coronal (c) CT angiograms of the abdomen show a high-attenuation collection centered in the second and third segments of the duodenum, consistent with hematoma (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig12b.jpeg" height="920" width="1069" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Duodenal trauma. <b>(a)</b> Duodenal contusion in a 63-year-old man following a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT angiogram shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with hyperattenuation, likely a duodenal hematoma (white arrow) with adjacent hemoperitoneum (*). Note the devascularization of the left kidney owing to injury to the left renal artery (black arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Duodenal hematoma in a 65-year-old man following blunt trauma to the abdomen. Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT angiograms of the abdomen show a high-attenuation collection centered in the second and third segments of the duodenum, consistent with hematoma (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal trauma. (a) Duodenal contusion in a 63-year-old man following a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT angiogram shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with hyperattenuation, likely a duodenal hematoma (white arrow) with adjacent hemoperitoneum (*). Note the devascularization of the left kidney owing to injury to the left renal artery (black arrow). (b, c) Duodenal hematoma in a 65-year-old man following blunt trauma to the abdomen. Axial (b) and coronal (c) CT angiograms of the abdomen show a high-attenuation collection centered in the second and third segments of the duodenum, consistent with hematoma (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig12c.jpeg" height="920" width="874" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Duodenal trauma. <b>(a)</b> Duodenal contusion in a 63-year-old man following a motor vehicle collision. Axial CT angiogram shows diffuse wall thickening of the duodenum with hyperattenuation, likely a duodenal hematoma (white arrow) with adjacent hemoperitoneum (*). Note the devascularization of the left kidney owing to injury to the left renal artery (black arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Duodenal hematoma in a 65-year-old man following blunt trauma to the abdomen. Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT angiograms of the abdomen show a high-attenuation collection centered in the second and third segments of the duodenum, consistent with hematoma (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal trauma in two patients. (a, b) Duodenal perforation in a 58-year-old man following a deceleration injury. Axial (a) and coronal (b) oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced abdominal CT images show foci of extraluminal gas (arrow), with wall thickening of the second segment of the duodenum (arrowhead). (c) Duodenal transection in a 66-year-old man following a motor vehicle injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows discontinuity of the duodenal wall (arrow) with extensive periduodenal hemorrhage (*). Note the liver laceration (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig13a.jpeg" height="1140" width="1243" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Duodenal trauma in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Duodenal perforation in a 58-year-old man following a deceleration injury. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced abdominal CT images show foci of extraluminal gas (arrow), with wall thickening of the second segment of the duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Duodenal transection in a 66-year-old man following a motor vehicle injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows discontinuity of the duodenal wall (arrow) with extensive periduodenal hemorrhage (*). Note the liver laceration (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal trauma in two patients. (a, b) Duodenal perforation in a 58-year-old man following a deceleration injury. Axial (a) and coronal (b) oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced abdominal CT images show foci of extraluminal gas (arrow), with wall thickening of the second segment of the duodenum (arrowhead). (c) Duodenal transection in a 66-year-old man following a motor vehicle injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows discontinuity of the duodenal wall (arrow) with extensive periduodenal hemorrhage (*). Note the liver laceration (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig13b.jpeg" height="1139" width="1260" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Duodenal trauma in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Duodenal perforation in a 58-year-old man following a deceleration injury. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced abdominal CT images show foci of extraluminal gas (arrow), with wall thickening of the second segment of the duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Duodenal transection in a 66-year-old man following a motor vehicle injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows discontinuity of the duodenal wall (arrow) with extensive periduodenal hemorrhage (*). Note the liver laceration (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal trauma in two patients. (a, b) Duodenal perforation in a 58-year-old man following a deceleration injury. Axial (a) and coronal (b) oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced abdominal CT images show foci of extraluminal gas (arrow), with wall thickening of the second segment of the duodenum (arrowhead). (c) Duodenal transection in a 66-year-old man following a motor vehicle injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows discontinuity of the duodenal wall (arrow) with extensive periduodenal hemorrhage (*). Note the liver laceration (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig13c.jpeg" height="1140" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Duodenal trauma in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Duodenal perforation in a 58-year-old man following a deceleration injury. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> oral and intravenous contrast-enhanced abdominal CT images show foci of extraluminal gas (arrow), with wall thickening of the second segment of the duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Duodenal transection in a 66-year-old man following a motor vehicle injury. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows discontinuity of the duodenal wall (arrow) with extensive periduodenal hemorrhage (*). Note the liver laceration (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Gastric outlet obstruction from a biopsy-proven duodenal adenocarcinoma in a 62-year-old man. (a) Coronal intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT image shows an infiltrative mass in the third segment of the duodenum causing near-complete obliteration of the duodenal lumen (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*). (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows a long nonopacified segment of the third segment of the duodenum (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig14a.jpeg" height="1126" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Gastric outlet obstruction from a biopsy-proven duodenal adenocarcinoma in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT image shows an infiltrative mass in the third segment of the duodenum causing near-complete obliteration of the duodenal lumen (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*). <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows a long nonopacified segment of the third segment of the duodenum (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Gastric outlet obstruction from a biopsy-proven duodenal adenocarcinoma in a 62-year-old man. (a) Coronal intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT image shows an infiltrative mass in the third segment of the duodenum causing near-complete obliteration of the duodenal lumen (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*). (b) Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows a long nonopacified segment of the third segment of the duodenum (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig14b.jpeg" height="1126" width="918" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Gastric outlet obstruction from a biopsy-proven duodenal adenocarcinoma in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT image shows an infiltrative mass in the third segment of the duodenum causing near-complete obliteration of the duodenal lumen (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*). <b>(b)</b> Image from upper gastrointestinal series shows a long nonopacified segment of the third segment of the duodenum (arrow) with dilatation of the stomach (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal metastatic disease in a 72-year-old woman with known lung cancer. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small focus of hemorrhage (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image obtained in the delayed phase shows change in the shape and mild increase in the size of the hemorrhage (arrow), findings consistent with active hemorrhage."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig15a.jpeg" height="1091" width="1174" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Duodenal metastatic disease in a 72-year-old woman with known lung cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small focus of hemorrhage (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained in the delayed phase shows change in the shape and mild increase in the size of the hemorrhage (arrow), findings consistent with active hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal metastatic disease in a 72-year-old woman with known lung cancer. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small focus of hemorrhage (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. (b) Axial CT image obtained in the delayed phase shows change in the shape and mild increase in the size of the hemorrhage (arrow), findings consistent with active hemorrhage."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig15b.jpeg" height="1090" width="1077" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Duodenal metastatic disease in a 72-year-old woman with known lung cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small focus of hemorrhage (arrow) in the second segment of the duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained in the delayed phase shows change in the shape and mild increase in the size of the hemorrhage (arrow), findings consistent with active hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenoduodenal intussusception in an 89-year-old woman. Coronal (a) and axial (b) CT images of the abdomen show a bowel-within-bowel appearance (arrow) owing to telescoping of one segment of the duodenum into another segment of the duodenum. Follow-up endoscopy (not shown) helped to confirm a duodenal mass, which was the lead point for the intussusception. The results of a biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig16a.jpeg" height="1409" width="1309" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Duodenoduodenal intussusception in an 89-year-old woman. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images of the abdomen show a bowel-within-bowel appearance (arrow) owing to telescoping of one segment of the duodenum into another segment of the duodenum. Follow-up endoscopy (not shown) helped to confirm a duodenal mass, which was the lead point for the intussusception. The results of a biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenoduodenal intussusception in an 89-year-old woman. Coronal (a) and axial (b) CT images of the abdomen show a bowel-within-bowel appearance (arrow) owing to telescoping of one segment of the duodenum into another segment of the duodenum. Follow-up endoscopy (not shown) helped to confirm a duodenal mass, which was the lead point for the intussusception. The results of a biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig16b.jpeg" height="1411" width="1353" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Duodenoduodenal intussusception in an 89-year-old woman. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images of the abdomen show a bowel-within-bowel appearance (arrow) owing to telescoping of one segment of the duodenum into another segment of the duodenum. Follow-up endoscopy (not shown) helped to confirm a duodenal mass, which was the lead point for the intussusception. The results of a biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Spontaneous duodenal hematoma in a 56-year-old man undergoing anticoagulant therapy who experienced sudden onset of abdominal pain. (a) Axial CT image of the abdomen shows high-attenuation material with focal areas of low attenuation within the second segment of the duodenum, consistent with duodenal hemorrhage (arrow). (b) Axial CT image obtained at follow-up 2 weeks later shows evolution of the hematoma (white arrow), which has decreased in size, and improved periduodenal hemorrhage (yellow arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig17a.jpeg" height="1207" width="1191" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Spontaneous duodenal hematoma in a 56-year-old man undergoing anticoagulant therapy who experienced sudden onset of abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the abdomen shows high-attenuation material with focal areas of low attenuation within the second segment of the duodenum, consistent with duodenal hemorrhage (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at follow-up 2 weeks later shows evolution of the hematoma (white arrow), which has decreased in size, and improved periduodenal hemorrhage (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Spontaneous duodenal hematoma in a 56-year-old man undergoing anticoagulant therapy who experienced sudden onset of abdominal pain. (a) Axial CT image of the abdomen shows high-attenuation material with focal areas of low attenuation within the second segment of the duodenum, consistent with duodenal hemorrhage (arrow). (b) Axial CT image obtained at follow-up 2 weeks later shows evolution of the hematoma (white arrow), which has decreased in size, and improved periduodenal hemorrhage (yellow arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig17b.jpeg" height="1207" width="1260" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Spontaneous duodenal hematoma in a 56-year-old man undergoing anticoagulant therapy who experienced sudden onset of abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the abdomen shows high-attenuation material with focal areas of low attenuation within the second segment of the duodenum, consistent with duodenal hemorrhage (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at follow-up 2 weeks later shows evolution of the hematoma (white arrow), which has decreased in size, and improved periduodenal hemorrhage (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="ADF in a 61-year-old woman after aortoiliac stent placement. (a) Axial CT angiogram in the arterial phase shows extensive periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (white arrow), with a small focus of intravenous contrast material in the third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow). (b, c) Coronal CT angiograms obtained in the arterial phase show periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (arrow in b) and a small amount of contrast material in the duodenum (arrow in c). The constellation of findings is consistent for ADF. The patient died less than 24 hours later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig18a.jpeg" height="850" width="1195" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. ADF in a 61-year-old woman after aortoiliac stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram in the arterial phase shows extensive periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (white arrow), with a small focus of intravenous contrast material in the third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT angiograms obtained in the arterial phase show periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (arrow in <b>b</b>) and a small amount of contrast material in the duodenum (arrow in <b>c</b>). The constellation of findings is consistent for ADF. The patient died less than 24 hours later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="ADF in a 61-year-old woman after aortoiliac stent placement. (a) Axial CT angiogram in the arterial phase shows extensive periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (white arrow), with a small focus of intravenous contrast material in the third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow). (b, c) Coronal CT angiograms obtained in the arterial phase show periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (arrow in b) and a small amount of contrast material in the duodenum (arrow in c). The constellation of findings is consistent for ADF. The patient died less than 24 hours later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig18b.jpeg" height="850" width="1088" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. ADF in a 61-year-old woman after aortoiliac stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram in the arterial phase shows extensive periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (white arrow), with a small focus of intravenous contrast material in the third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT angiograms obtained in the arterial phase show periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (arrow in <b>b</b>) and a small amount of contrast material in the duodenum (arrow in <b>c</b>). The constellation of findings is consistent for ADF. The patient died less than 24 hours later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic" aria-label="ADF in a 61-year-old woman after aortoiliac stent placement. (a) Axial CT angiogram in the arterial phase shows extensive periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (white arrow), with a small focus of intravenous contrast material in the third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow). (b, c) Coronal CT angiograms obtained in the arterial phase show periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (arrow in b) and a small amount of contrast material in the duodenum (arrow in c). The constellation of findings is consistent for ADF. The patient died less than 24 hours later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig18c.jpeg" height="851" width="1119" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. ADF in a 61-year-old woman after aortoiliac stent placement. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram in the arterial phase shows extensive periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (white arrow), with a small focus of intravenous contrast material in the third segment of the duodenum (yellow arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal CT angiograms obtained in the arterial phase show periaortic stranding and soft-tissue thickening (arrow in <b>b</b>) and a small amount of contrast material in the duodenum (arrow in <b>c</b>). The constellation of findings is consistent for ADF. The patient died less than 24 hours later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="SMA syndrome in a 37-year-old woman. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows significant decrease in the distance between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric distance), measuring 4 mm (arrow). (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a decrease in the angle between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric angle) (circle) to 12°."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig19a.jpeg" height="1103" width="1688" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. SMA syndrome in a 37-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows significant decrease in the distance between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric distance), measuring 4 mm (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a decrease in the angle between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric angle) (circle) to 12°.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="SMA syndrome in a 37-year-old woman. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows significant decrease in the distance between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric distance), measuring 4 mm (arrow). (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a decrease in the angle between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric angle) (circle) to 12°."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig19b.jpeg" height="1103" width="954" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. SMA syndrome in a 37-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows significant decrease in the distance between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric distance), measuring 4 mm (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a decrease in the angle between the aorta and the SMA (aortomesenteric angle) (circle) to 12°.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal hemorrhage secondary to rupture of an inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery aneurysm in a 65-year-old man. (a) Axial CT angiogram of the abdomen shows a 7-mm aneurysm (dashed circle) with surrounding hematoma (*). (b) Angiogram shows a 7-mm aneurysm in the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery (arrow), which was coiled. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig20a.jpeg" height="1070" width="1156" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Duodenal hemorrhage secondary to rupture of an inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery aneurysm in a 65-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram of the abdomen shows a 7-mm aneurysm (dashed circle) with surrounding hematoma (*). <b>(b)</b> Angiogram shows a 7-mm aneurysm in the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery (arrow), which was coiled. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal hemorrhage secondary to rupture of an inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery aneurysm in a 65-year-old man. (a) Axial CT angiogram of the abdomen shows a 7-mm aneurysm (dashed circle) with surrounding hematoma (*). (b) Angiogram shows a 7-mm aneurysm in the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery (arrow), which was coiled. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig20b.jpeg" height="1070" width="1086" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Duodenal hemorrhage secondary to rupture of an inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery aneurysm in a 65-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram of the abdomen shows a 7-mm aneurysm (dashed circle) with surrounding hematoma (*). <b>(b)</b> Angiogram shows a 7-mm aneurysm in the inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery (arrow), which was coiled. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal diverticulitis in a 45-year-old woman. (a) Coronal enhanced CT image shows an outpouching from the medial wall of the second segment of the duodenum, representing a noninflamed diverticulum (arrow) as an incidental finding. (b) Coronal enhanced CT image obtained after the patient presented with abdominal pain months later shows fluid in the diverticulum, with extensive surrounding fat stranding (dashed oval) and wall thickening, consistent with acute duodenal diverticulitis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig21a.jpeg" height="1173" width="1111" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Duodenal diverticulitis in a 45-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal enhanced CT image shows an outpouching from the medial wall of the second segment of the duodenum, representing a noninflamed diverticulum (arrow) as an incidental finding. <b>(b)</b> Coronal enhanced CT image obtained after the patient presented with abdominal pain months later shows fluid in the diverticulum, with extensive surrounding fat stranding (dashed oval) and wall thickening, consistent with acute duodenal diverticulitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic" aria-label="Duodenal diverticulitis in a 45-year-old woman. (a) Coronal enhanced CT image shows an outpouching from the medial wall of the second segment of the duodenum, representing a noninflamed diverticulum (arrow) as an incidental finding. (b) Coronal enhanced CT image obtained after the patient presented with abdominal pain months later shows fluid in the diverticulum, with extensive surrounding fat stranding (dashed oval) and wall thickening, consistent with acute duodenal diverticulitis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig21b.jpeg" height="1171" width="1138" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Duodenal diverticulitis in a 45-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal enhanced CT image shows an outpouching from the medial wall of the second segment of the duodenum, representing a noninflamed diverticulum (arrow) as an incidental finding. <b>(b)</b> Coronal enhanced CT image obtained after the patient presented with abdominal pain months later shows fluid in the diverticulum, with extensive surrounding fat stranding (dashed oval) and wall thickening, consistent with acute duodenal diverticulitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic" aria-label="Bezoar in the duodenum. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows low attenuation and heterogenous material filling and distending the stomach and the second and third segments of the duodenum (arrows). (b) Endoscopic image shows a large hair-containing mass, consistent with a trichobezoar. (c) Photograph shows a large trichobezoar that was surgically removed. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig22a.jpeg" height="1125" width="1306" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Bezoar in the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows low attenuation and heterogenous material filling and distending the stomach and the second and third segments of the duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows a large hair-containing mass, consistent with a trichobezoar. <b>(c)</b> Photograph shows a large trichobezoar that was surgically removed. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic" aria-label="Bezoar in the duodenum. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows low attenuation and heterogenous material filling and distending the stomach and the second and third segments of the duodenum (arrows). (b) Endoscopic image shows a large hair-containing mass, consistent with a trichobezoar. (c) Photograph shows a large trichobezoar that was surgically removed. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig22b.jpeg" height="1125" width="1220" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Bezoar in the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows low attenuation and heterogenous material filling and distending the stomach and the second and third segments of the duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows a large hair-containing mass, consistent with a trichobezoar. <b>(c)</b> Photograph shows a large trichobezoar that was surgically removed. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic" aria-label="Bezoar in the duodenum. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows low attenuation and heterogenous material filling and distending the stomach and the second and third segments of the duodenum (arrows). (b) Endoscopic image shows a large hair-containing mass, consistent with a trichobezoar. (c) Photograph shows a large trichobezoar that was surgically removed. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200045/asset/images/large/rg.2020200045.fig22c.jpeg" height="1125" width="1195" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Bezoar in the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows low attenuation and heterogenous material filling and distending the stomach and the second and third segments of the duodenum (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows a large hair-containing mass, consistent with a trichobezoar. <b>(c)</b> Photograph shows a large trichobezoar that was surgically removed. (Case courtesy of Jennifer W. Uyeda, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200045&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section>